A senior lecturer in the University of Port Harcourt, Professor Eme Ekekwe, has called for investment in agriculture, health care, restructuring of the economy, reduction in the cost of governance, and possible home a grown solution to coronavirus in a post-COVID-19 pandemic in Nigeria. Ekekwe made the call in Port Harcourt while speaking at a June 12 Conversation, with the title; “The Challenges of Post Pandemic Nigeria” organized by a good governance advocacy group, the Unity House Foundation (UHF). He stated that the coronavirus pandemic exposed Nigeria’s “underbelly and made nonsense of our democracy,” pointing out that the country must change ways of doing things if the desired results are to be achieved. Also speaking, another speaker at the event, Onyekachi Omenuko noted the COVID-19 pandemic exposed our inadequacies in the health sector, adding that going forward, governments at all levels must invest in the health sector and provide quality services to the generality of the people. Omenuko explained further that agriculture must be given the priority it deserves, especially in its ability to create employment, ensure food security, boost Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and earn foreign exchange. Earlier in his welcome remarks, Convener of Unity House Foundation (UHF), Kingsley Wenenda Wali, who stated that Nigerians must tell the truth to themselves, said Nigerians started paying attention to democracy after the June 12 saga. Wali, who said nobody was prepared for the coronavirus pandemic, insisted that the country must urgently tackle challenges in the health sector, agriculture, economy, and transport, amongst others. He noted that the first step going forward is that the country must admit there are problems that require difficult decisions to be made in the interest of the people.  